    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load metric.csv, trace.csv, log.csv, and error_logs.csv into kernel dataframes named metric_df, trace_df, log_df, error_logs_df. For each dataframe, compute and return a compact summary containing: 1) total row count, 2) list of unique cmdb_id values (limit to top 20), 3) list of unique KPI/feature column names (metric: unique kpi_name, trace: unique trace_name, log: unique log_name) (limit to top 50), 4) minimum and maximum timestamp values, and 5) the top 5 rows as a preview. Store the full dataframes in the kernel for later steps but do not print full tables. Return results as a small JSON-like dictionary for each file." 
}

{
    "analysis": "Executor loaded all four telemetry files and returned a compact catalog: metric.csv (29,749 rows) and trace.csv (7,071 rows) cover the full incident window 2021-03-25 11:30 to 12:00 (UTC+8); log.csv is sparse (502 rows) and error_logs.csv is empty. This confirms we have dense metric and trace coverage to perform metric-first anomaly detection, while logs likely provide limited additional signal. Next step should be metric-based preprocessing and anomaly scanning: calculate global thresholds (P95) for every component-KPI time series using the full available metric series (per rules), then filter metric points to the incident window and detect points that exceed their global P95. From that we can shortlist the top component-KPI candidates (by anomaly count and severity) for deeper trace and log analysis. No further derivation is possible yet because thresholds and anomaly counts have not been computed.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the already-loaded metric_df in kernel, perform the following and store intermediate results in kernel variables:\n1) For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) in metric_df (use the full available timestamps), compute the global P95 value and save as thresholds_df with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, p95_threshold.\n2) Filter metric_df to the incident time window inclusive: timestamps between 2021-03-25 11:30:00+08:00 and 2021-03-25 12:00:00+08:00; save as metric_incident_df.\n3) For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) present in metric_incident_df, count how many incident-window points have value >= p95_threshold (join with thresholds_df). For each pair compute: anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_ts (first timestamp in incident window where value >= threshold), max_value_in_window, p95_threshold, and max_over_threshold_ratio = max_value_in_window / p95_threshold.\n4) Return a compact table of the top 20 rows sorted by anomaly_count desc (tie-breaker: max_over_threshold_ratio desc) with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_ts, p95_threshold, max_value_in_window, max_over_threshold_ratio. Also return the total number of distinct (cmdb_id, kpi_name) series scanned and store thresholds_df and metric_incident_df in the kernel for later steps."
}

{
    "analysis": "The previous step computed global P95 thresholds for 1,754 (cmdb_id, kpi_name) series and scanned the incident window (31 minutes). Many series (top candidates) show anomalies at every minute in the window (anomaly_count=31). Most of those are JVM memory KPIs with max_over_threshold_ratio ≈ 1.00 (barely at P95); one notable metric (MG01 zabbix agent process KPI) shows ratio ≈ 1.33. Because many series are constant at or above their P95 across the whole window, we cannot yet pick the single root cause component. The next logical narrowing step is to aggregate anomalies at the component (cmdb_id) level to find which components have the largest number of anomalous KPIs, the largest total anomaly points, and the greatest severity (max_over_threshold_ratio). This will produce a short-ranked candidate list for targeted trace and log analysis.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using thresholds_df and metric_incident_df stored in the kernel, aggregate anomaly results by cmdb_id as follows and store the result as component_anomaly_df in the kernel:\n1) For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) present in metric_incident_df, determine if it has any anomaly points in the incident window (value >= corresponding p95_threshold). Use the previously computed per-series anomaly_count and earliest_anomaly_ts and max_over_threshold_ratio values if available; otherwise compute them from metric_incident_df joined with thresholds_df.\n2) For each cmdb_id compute: num_kpi_anomalies = count of distinct kpi_name with anomaly_count>0; total_anomaly_points = sum of anomaly_count across its KPIs; earliest_anomaly_ts = earliest anomaly timestamp among its KPIs; max_over_threshold_ratio = maximum max_over_threshold_ratio among its KPIs; top_kpi = the kpi_name with the highest max_over_threshold_ratio for that cmdb_id.\n3) Return a compact table of the top 20 components sorted by total_anomaly_points desc (tie-breaker by max_over_threshold_ratio desc) with columns: cmdb_id, num_kpi_anomalies, total_anomaly_points, earliest_anomaly_ts, max_over_threshold_ratio, top_kpi. Also return the total number of components scanned. Store component_anomaly_df in the kernel for next steps."
}

{
    "analysis": "Trace analysis found that MG01 and MG02 have the largest number of trace anomalies (many trace.* latency KPIs exceed their global P95 from the start of the window), several docker nodes and Tomcat instances also show elevated trace anomalies, and IG01 traces began showing anomalies slightly later (11:32). Metrics show widespread sustained anomalies across many components starting at 2021-03-25T11:30:00+08:00, with Mysql nodes and Tomcats among the most affected by total anomaly points. Because many components are anomalous simultaneously, we cannot decide the single root cause from metrics alone. According to the workflow, we now need to inspect trace edges (trace.to_* and trace.from_*) to identify the most downstream faulty service in call chains and find which component shows the earliest and/or largest trace degradation. This will narrow candidates for final log inspection.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using thresholds_trace_df and trace_incident_df stored in the kernel, aggregate trace-edge anomalies focusing on trace names that reference 'from_' or 'to_' relationships. Do the following and store results in kernel as trace_edge_agg_df:\n1) For each distinct (cmdb_id, trace_name) in trace_incident_df, compute: count_high (value >= p95_threshold), earliest_high_ts (first ts where value >= p95_threshold), p95_threshold, max_value_in_window, max_over_p95 = max_value_in_window / p95_threshold (NaN if p95==0). Also compute count_low and earliest_low_ts against p5_threshold from thresholds_trace_df for completeness.\n2) Parse trace_name to extract direction ('from' or 'to' or 'self') and the referenced component (e.g., 'trace.to_MG01.duration_mean' -> direction='to', target='MG01'; 'trace.from_IG02.duration_p95' -> direction='from', target='IG02'; 'trace.self.*' -> direction='self', target=cmdb_id).\n3) Filter to trace-edge rows where direction is 'to' or 'from' (keep 'self' only if max_over_p95>1.5). Return a compact table of the top 20 trace-edge series sorted by max_over_p95 desc (tie-breaker: count_high desc) with columns: cmdb_id, trace_name, direction, target_component, count_high, earliest_high_ts, p95_threshold, max_value_in_window, max_over_p95. Also return a short list of distinct target_component values present in these top rows.\nLimit returned rows to 20 and keep the output compact. Store trace_edge_agg_df in the kernel for next steps."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have completed metric and trace thresholding and aggregated anomalies to the component level. Key facts from the aggregated results: many components show sustained metric anomalies across the whole 31-minute window starting at 2021-03-25T11:30:00+08:00 (Mysql nodes and Tomcat/Redis fleets have the largest metric anomaly volumes). Trace analysis shows MG01/MG02 and several docker/Tomcat nodes have pronounced trace-edge spikes (e.g., dockerB2 self ~4x P95; symmetric dockerA1<->MG02 and dockerB1<->MG01 edges ~2.4–2.7x P95). Combined_component_df lists components anomalous in both metrics and traces (IG01/IG02, MG01/MG02, Tomcat01–04, dockerA2). No error logs or non-zero log.error_count were found to corroborate failures.\n\nWhat we still cannot conclude: a single root-cause component. Multiple components are faulty simultaneously. According to the localization rules, we must (1) use trace call relationships to identify the most downstream component(s) that are actually faulty, and (2) use the earliest occurrence time plus severity to pick the root cause. We need a focused trace-edge view that maps calls between the metric-faulty components (caller -> callee) and reports earliest anomaly timestamps and severity per edge so we can identify downstream faulty nodes that appear as targets of degraded edges and which show severe metric deviations.\n\nTherefore we must inspect trace edges where the target (callee) is itself metric-faulty, and examine earliest trace anomaly times and severity so we can identify the most downstream faulty service in the call chains. This is the next narrowing step toward final localization.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From the stored trace_edge_agg_df in the kernel, produce a compact table of trace edges where the target_component is present in the set of components that have metric anomalies (component_anomaly_df with metric_total_anomaly_points>0). For each matching row return: source_component(cmdb_id), trace_name, direction, target_component, earliest_high_ts (earliest timestamp where value>=p95), count_high, p95_threshold, max_value_in_window, max_over_p95. Sort the results primarily by earliest_high_ts ascending (earliest first) and secondarily by max_over_p95 descending. Limit output to the top 20 rows. Also return a short deduplicated list of target_component values present in these filtered rows. Store the filtered table as trace_edges_to_metric_faults_df in the kernel for the next step."
}

{
    "analysis": "Executor filtered trace edges whose target components also show metric anomalies and returned a compact set of edges (trace_edges_to_metric_faults_df). Results show 20+ edges where many callers (docker nodes, IG, Tomcat) invoke targets that are metric-faulty (MG01, MG02, Tomcat03, IG02, IG01, Tomcat01, Tomcat02, dockerA2). Earliest observed edge anomalies occur at 2021-03-25T11:30:00+08:00 and several early edges (11:30–11:34) target MG02 and MG01. Many edges have mild relative spikes (max_over_p95 ≈ 1.01–1.37) but a few edges (e.g., MG01 -> dockerA2 and dockerA1 -> MG02) show stronger relative severity (>1.3 and up to ~1.52). Distinct target components in these filtered edges are: dockerA2, MG02, MG01, Tomcat03, IG02, Tomcat01, IG01, Tomcat02. From this we can derive that MG01 and MG02 are heavily implicated as targets of anomalous inbound edges early in the window and that several Tomcat and IG services are also involved. However, multiple components are faulty simultaneously and we cannot yet unambiguously pick a single root-cause component. To decide, we need to compare, per edge, whether the upstream caller is metric-faulty or healthy and whether the downstream target has the earliest and most severe metric fault. Specifically, edges where the target is metric-faulty but the source is not suggest the target is the root cause (downstream faulty), while edges where the caller is faulty but the callee is not suggest propagation. This comparison will help identify the most downstream faulty component in call chains and the earliest exact occurrence time.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From the stored trace_edges_to_metric_faults_df and combined_component_df in the kernel, produce a compact edge-level table that joins caller and callee metric-fault info. For each edge row return: source_component (cmdb_id), target_component, trace_name, earliest_high_ts (trace edge), count_high, max_over_p95, source_metric_total_anomaly_points (0 if absent), source_metric_earliest_ts (NULL if absent), source_metric_max_ratio (NULL if absent), target_metric_total_anomaly_points (0 if absent), target_metric_earliest_ts (NULL if absent), target_metric_max_ratio (NULL if absent). Sort rows by earliest_high_ts asc, then by target_metric_max_ratio desc. Limit to top 20 rows. Also return a small deduplicated list of edges where (target_metric_total_anomaly_points>0 and source_metric_total_anomaly_points==0) — these edges are strong candidates where the callee (target) may be the root cause. Store the resulting table as edge_source_target_metric_join_df in the kernel for final localization."
}

{
    "analysis": "We completed preprocess -> anomaly detection -> fault identification -> localization steps using metrics, traces, and logs. Evidence summary: thresholds computed for all component-KPI series; metric anomalies aggregated per (component,KPI) and then per component; trace anomalies aggregated and parsed into from/to/self edges; we joined trace edges with component metric summaries to identify edges where callers were healthy but callees showed metric faults. Prioritization combining metric severity (max_over_p95), anomaly volume, trace support, and inbound-healthy-callers produced MG02 as the top candidate. Detailed MG02 inspection shows: (a) sustained metric anomalies starting at 2021-03-25T11:30:00+08:00 (some CPU metrics), (b) pronounced disk-related KPI spikes (OSLinux LOCALDISK sda/sdb: DSKRead/DSKWrite/DSKBps/DSKRTps) with the earliest disk-related threshold breach at 2021-03-25T11:40:00+08:00 and large severity (max_over_p95 up to ~4.0), (c) elevated CPU iowait concurrent with disk spikes, and (d) inbound trace edges from callers that show trace latency spikes while those callers have no metric faults (e.g., dockerA1/B1/B2 calling MG02). Logs and error_logs contain no error_count or error entries to contradict this. According to the localization rules, the root cause should be the most downstream faulty service in traces with significant deviation; MG02 satisfies this (callee severely faulty, healthy callers, early occurrence). The earliest disk-related KPI fault (the most plausible root-cause signal for the observed platform-wide latency) occurs at 2021-03-25T11:40:00+08:00 (sdb_DSKWrite) with larger disk spikes following at 11:42 and 11:56. Therefore disk I/O saturation on MG02, causing high I/O wait and service latency, is the most likely root cause.",
    "completed": "True",
    "instruction": "Conclusion and recommended summary (final answer):\nRoot cause component: MG02\nRoot cause occurrence datetime (UTC+8): 2021-03-25T11:40:00+08:00 (first disk-related KPI breach on MG02; note some CPU metrics rose earlier at 11:30 but the dominant disk I/O faults begin at 11:40)\nRoot cause reason: High local disk I/O on MG02 (sda/sdb high read/write throughput and high request rates/latencies) leading to elevated CPU I/O-wait and degraded service latency. Evidence: large metric anomaly volume and severity on MG02 (many KPIs above P95, disk KPIs max_over_p95 up to ~4.0), many inbound trace latency/row_count anomalies targeting MG02 while callers show no metric faults (directional support), and temporal correlation of disk spikes with increased trace latencies.\nRecommended immediate actions: investigate MG02 disk subsystem (per-device I/O, queue lengths, processes performing heavy I/O), reduce or throttle heavy I/O workloads if possible, and investigate system-level remedies (I/O scheduler/tuning, offload or reschedule jobs). Correlate MG02 system logs around 11:40–11:56 for more context (kernel, process-level I/O activity)."
}

